# TagKin Desktop — Cursor Agent Rules

# Project scope
- This repo (`tagkin-desktop`) is the Flutter/Dart desktop client for TagKin
  (Windows and macOS only for now; no iOS/Android until product says otherwise).
- Product name: TagKin — orchestration for family photos/videos that auto-tags and
  links people without TagKin servers reading or storing user media bytes.
- Canonical product/architecture docs live in the sibling **`tagkin`** repo under
  `Docs/` — not in this repo.

# Canonical documentation (required)
- Read and obey (via sibling path or multi-root workspace):
  - `tagkin/Docs/Rules.md` (hard constraints R1–R7)
  - `tagkin/Docs/Specs_Initial.md`
  - `tagkin/Docs/Tech_Solutions.md`
  - `tagkin/Docs/System_Design.md` (includes client strategy, §2.1)
- This repo keeps only a thin `README.md` for desktop build/run. Do **not** copy
  or fork product Docs here.
- When a change affects product behavior, API usage, or hard rules, update the
  relevant file under `tagkin/Docs/` in the **same change** (or call out that the
  docs edit must land in the `tagkin` repo in the same PR/commit set). Prefer
  amending existing sections and changelog rows.
- Desktop-only setup details may stay in this README.
- If code and Docs disagree, fix whichever is wrong; do not leave them out of sync.

# Hard rules (summary — full text in tagkin/Docs/Rules.md)
- **R1 / R5 / R7** — TagKin servers never hold media bytes. Desktop may read local
  files and upload client → model host / client → user cloud; never upload media
  bytes into TagKin storage or through the API as a media vault.
- **R2** — UI terms ≡ code terms. Prefer models generated from `@tagkin/contract`
  so Dart names match TypeScript/DB. Do not invent synonyms for Item, Tag, Person,
  Key period, etc.
- **R6** — Person likeness suggestions need human confirm/correct UI.

# Platform targets
- **Targets:** Windows and macOS desktop.
- Write shared logic in `lib/` to be platform-agnostic; isolate OS-specific code
  in services/plugins.
- Use `dart:io` Platform checks only at init boundaries and inside services — not
  scattered through widgets.
- Avoid hard-coded OS paths; use path_provider / app path helpers.
- Prefer packages with Windows + macOS desktop support.

# Architecture (Flutter)
- Keep business logic out of widgets; use services / state notifiers (or the
  state pattern already in the tree once scaffolding exists).
- Prefer Riverpod (or the project’s chosen state library) for shared state; avoid
  global mutable singletons.
- Match existing naming, import style, and folder layout.

# Dart / Flutter conventions
- Package name: follow `pubspec.yaml` (import as that package).
- Use async/await; never block the UI isolate.
- Use explicit model classes; avoid dynamic and reflection.
- Prefer const constructors and widgets where possible.
- Run `flutter analyze` after substantive edits; keep zero analyzer issues.
- Do not add packages without clear need; prefer what is already in pubspec.yaml.
- Native plugins require per-platform rebuilds (Windows: VS C++; macOS: Xcode).

# IMPORTANT: Workflow (required)
You must always follow this workflow:

1. Before making any changes, you must produce a clear, structured plan.
   - The plan must describe the steps you intend to take.
   - The plan must list which files you will read or modify.
   - The plan must explain the reasoning behind the steps.
   - The plan must not make any code changes.

2. After producing the plan, you must stop and wait for my confirmation.
   - Do not execute the plan automatically.
   - Do not generate diffs.
   - Do not modify any files until I explicitly approve the plan.

3. When I approve the plan, you will run the agent to execute it.
   - Only then may you generate diffs and modify files.
   - Stay within the scope of the approved plan.
   - If new information appears that requires changing the plan, pause and request approval again.

4. Never skip the planning step.
   Never combine planning and execution in the same response.
   Never modify files without an approved plan.

Your behavior must always follow this sequence:
PLAN → WAIT → EXECUTE (AGENT)

# IMPORTANT: Restart guidance (required)
- **Always** end every reply that includes code or config changes with a clear **Restart**
  line telling the user exactly how to apply the change. Do not skip this, even for small edits.
- Pick one (or explain why more than one is needed):
  - **Hot reload / hot sync** — Dart-only UI/logic changes; no native/plugin/init changes.
  - **Hot restart** — state reset needed (providers, initState, route changes).
  - **Full restart** — stop and re-run `flutter run -d windows` (or macOS); process must restart.
  - **Rebuild** — native code, plugins, pubspec dependencies, assets, or CMake/Xcode files changed;
    rebuild before running again.
- Be specific to the change just made.
- If no code changed (question-only reply), omit the Restart line.

# Maintainability
- Minimize diff scope; do not refactor unrelated code.
- No over-abstraction; reuse existing services and widgets.
- Comments only for non-obvious logic.
- Prefer contract-generated Dart models over hand-maintained duplicates (R2).
